    # master_password - (Optional) (Required unless a `snapshot_identifier` is provided) Password for the master DB user.
    master_password = ""

    # master_username - (Optional) (Required unless a `snapshot_identifier` is provided) Username for the master DB user.
    master_username = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # vpc_security_group_ids - (Optional) A list of Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) security groups to be associated with the cluster.
    vpc_security_group_ids = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # cluster_subnet_group_name - (Optional) The name of a cluster subnet group to be associated with this cluster. If this parameter is not provided the resulting cluster will be deployed outside virtual private cloud (VPC).
    cluster_subnet_group_name = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # availability_zone - (Optional) The EC2 Availability Zone (AZ) in which you want Amazon Redshift to provision the cluster. For example, if you have several EC2 instances running in a specific Availability Zone, then you might want the cluster to be provisioned in the same zone in order to decrease network latency.
    availability_zone = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # preferred_maintenance_window - (Optional) The weekly time range (in UTC) during which automated cluster maintenance can occur.
    preferred_maintenance_window = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # cluster_parameter_group_name - (Optional) The name of the parameter group to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_parameter_group_name = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # automated_snapshot_retention_period - (Optional) The number of days that automated snapshots are retained. If the value is 0, automated snapshots are disabled. Even if automated snapshots are disabled, you can still create manual snapshots when you want with create-cluster-snapshot. Default is 1.
    automated_snapshot_retention_period = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # port - (Optional) The port number on which the cluster accepts incoming connections.
    port = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # cluster_version - (Optional) The version of the Amazon Redshift engine software that you want to deploy on the cluster.
    cluster_version = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # allow_version_upgrade - (Optional) If true , major version upgrades can be applied during the maintenance window to the Amazon Redshift engine that is running on the cluster. Default is true
    allow_version_upgrade = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # number_of_nodes - (Optional) The number of compute nodes in the cluster. This parameter is required when the ClusterType parameter is specified as multi-node. Default is 1.
    number_of_nodes = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # publicly_accessible - (Optional) If true, the cluster can be accessed from a public network. Default is `true`.
    publicly_accessible = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # encrypted - (Optional) If true , the data in the cluster is encrypted at rest.
    encrypted = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # enhanced_vpc_routing - (Optional) If true , enhanced VPC routing is enabled.
    enhanced_vpc_routing = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # kms_key_id - (Optional) The ARN for the KMS encryption key. When specifying `kms_key_id`, `encrypted` needs to be set to true.
    kms_key_id = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # elastic_ip - (Optional) The Elastic IP (EIP) address for the cluster.
    elastic_ip = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # skip_final_snapshot - (Optional) Determines whether a final snapshot of the cluster is created before Amazon Redshift deletes the cluster. If true , a final cluster snapshot is not created. If false , a final cluster snapshot is created before the cluster is deleted. Default is false.
    skip_final_snapshot = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # final_snapshot_identifier - (Optional) The identifier of the final snapshot that is to be created immediately before deleting the cluster. If this parameter is provided, `skip_final_snapshot` must be false.
    final_snapshot_identifier = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # snapshot_identifier - (Optional) The name of the snapshot from which to create the new cluster.
    snapshot_identifier = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # snapshot_cluster_identifier - (Optional) The name of the cluster the source snapshot was created from.
    snapshot_cluster_identifier = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # owner_account - (Optional) The AWS customer account used to create or copy the snapshot. Required if you are restoring a snapshot you do not own, optional if you own the snapshot.
    owner_account = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # iam_roles - (Optional) A list of IAM Role ARNs to associate with the cluster. A Maximum of 10 can be associated to the cluster at any time.

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # enable_logging - (Optional) Enables logging information such as queries and connection attempts, for the specified Amazon Redshift cluster. Defaults to `false`.
    enable_logging = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.

    # bucket_name - (Optional) (Optional, required when `enable_logging` is `true`) The name of an existing S3 bucket where the log files are to be stored. Must be in the same region as the cluster and the cluster must have read bucket and put object permissions.
    bucket_name = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # tags - (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
    tags = ""

    # cluster_security_groups - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    cluster_security_groups = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The Redshift Cluster ID.
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "cluster_identifier" - The Cluster Identifier
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "cluster_type" - The cluster type
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "node_type" - The type of nodes in the cluster
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "database_name" - The name of the default database in the Cluster
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "availability_zone" - The availability zone of the Cluster
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "automated_snapshot_retention_period" - The backup retention period
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "preferred_maintenance_window" - The backup window
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "endpoint" - The connection endpoint
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "encrypted" - Whether the data in the cluster is encrypted
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "cluster_security_groups" - The security groups associated with the cluster
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "vpc_security_group_ids" - The VPC security group Ids associated with the cluster
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "port" - The Port the cluster responds on

    # "cluster_version" - The version of Redshift engine software
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "cluster_parameter_group_name" - The name of the parameter group to be associated with this cluster
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "cluster_subnet_group_name" - The name of a cluster subnet group to be associated with this cluster
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "cluster_public_key" - The public key for the cluster
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
    # "cluster_revision_number" - The specific revision number of the database in the cluster
    # "cluster_security_groups" - (Optional) A list of security groups to be associated with this cluster.
}

    # network_interface_id - (Optional) The ID of the elastic network interface (eni) to use.
    network_interface_id = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the routing table

aws-resource-route-table|.description:
Provides a resource to create a VPC routing table. ~> **NOTE on Route Tables and Routes:** Terraform currently
provides both a standalone [Route resource](route.html) and a Route Table resource with routes
defined in-line. At this time you cannot use a Route Table with in-line routes
in conjunction with any Route resources. Doing so will cause
a conflict of rule settings and will overwrite rules. ~> **NOTE on `gateway_id` and `nat_gateway_id`:** The AWS API is very forgiving with these two
attributes and the `aws_route_table` resource can be created with a NAT ID specified as a Gateway ID attribute.
This _will_ lead to a permanent diff between your configuration and statefile, as the API returns the correct
parameters in the returned route table. If you're experiencing constant diffs in your `aws_route_table` resources,
the first thing to check is whether or not you're specifying a NAT ID instead of a Gateway ID, or vice-versa. ~> **NOTE on `propagating_vgws` and the `aws_vpn_gateway_route_propagation` resource:**
If the `propagating_vgws` argument is present, it's not supported to _also_
define route propagations using `aws_vpn_gateway_route_propagation`, since
this resource will delete any propagating gateways not explicitly listed in
`propagating_vgws`. Omit this argument when defining route propagation using
the separate resource.

aws-resource-route53-health-check.body:
resource "aws_route53_health_check" "$1" {
    # request_interval - (Required) The number of seconds between the time that Amazon Route 53 gets a response from your endpoint and the time that it sends the next health-check request.
    request_interval = ""

    # failure_threshold - (Required) The number of consecutive health checks that an endpoint must pass or fail.
    failure_threshold = ""

    # type - (Required) The protocol to use when performing health checks. Valid values are `HTTP`, `HTTPS`, `HTTP_STR_MATCH`, `HTTPS_STR_MATCH`, `TCP`, `CALCULATED` and `CLOUDWATCH_METRIC`.
    type = ""

    # reference_name - (Optional) This is a reference name used in Caller Reference
    reference_name = ""

    # fqdn - (Optional) The fully qualified domain name of the endpoint to be checked.
    fqdn = ""

    # ip_address - (Optional) The IP address of the endpoint to be checked.
    ip_address = ""

    # port - (Optional) The port of the endpoint to be checked.
    port = ""

    # resource_path - (Optional) The path that you want Amazon Route 53 to request when performing health checks.
    resource_path = ""

    # search_string - (Optional) String searched in the first 5120 bytes of the response body for check to be considered healthy.
    search_string = ""

    # measure_latency - (Optional) A Boolean value that indicates whether you want Route 53 to measure the latency between health checkers in multiple AWS regions and your endpoint and to display CloudWatch latency graphs in the Route 53 console.
    measure_latency = ""

    # invert_healthcheck - (Optional) A boolean value that indicates whether the status of health check should be inverted. For example, if a health check is healthy but Inverted is True , then Route 53 considers the health check to be unhealthy.
    invert_healthcheck = ""

    # enable_sni - (Optional) A boolean value that indicates whether Route53 should send the `fqdn` to the endpoint when performing the health check. This defaults to AWS' defaults: when the `type` is "HTTPS" `enable_sni` defaults to `true`, when `type` is anything else `enable_sni` defaults to `false`.
    enable_sni = ""

    # child_healthchecks - (Optional) For a specified parent health check, a list of HealthCheckId values for the associated child health checks.
    child_healthchecks = ""

    # child_health_threshold - (Optional) The minimum number of child health checks that must be healthy for Route 53 to consider the parent health check to be healthy. Valid values are integers between 0 and 256, inclusive
    child_health_threshold = ""

    # cloudwatch_alarm_name - (Optional) The name of the CloudWatch alarm.
    cloudwatch_alarm_name = ""

    # cloudwatch_alarm_region - (Optional) The CloudWatchRegion that the CloudWatch alarm was created in.
    cloudwatch_alarm_region = ""

    # insufficient_data_health_status - (Optional) The status of the health check when CloudWatch has insufficient data about the state of associated alarm. Valid values are `Healthy` , `Unhealthy` and `LastKnownStatus`.
    insufficient_data_health_status = ""

    # regions - (Optional) A list of AWS regions that you want Amazon Route 53 health checkers to check the specified endpoint from.
    regions = ""

    # tags - (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the health check.
    tags = ""

    # Exported Attributes
}

aws-resource-route53-record.body:
resource "aws_route53_record" "$1" {
    # weight - (Required) A numeric value indicating the relative weight of the record. See http://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/routing-policy.html#routing-policy-weighted.
    weight = ""

    # region - (Required) An AWS region from which to measure latency. See http://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/routing-policy.html#routing-policy-latency
    region = ""

    # type - (Required) `PRIMARY` or `SECONDARY`. A `PRIMARY` record will be served if its healthcheck is passing, otherwise the `SECONDARY` will be served. See http://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/dns-failover-configuring-options.html#dns-failover-failover-rrsets
    type = ""

    # evaluate_target_health - (Required) Set to `true` if you want Route 53 to determine whether to respond to DNS queries using this resource record set by checking the health of the resource record set. Some resources have special requirements, see [related part of documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/resource-record-sets-values.html#rrsets-values-alias-evaluate-target-health).
    evaluate_target_health = ""

    # zone_id - (Required) Hosted zone ID for a CloudFront distribution, S3 bucket, ELB, or Route 53 hosted zone. See [`resource_elb.zone_id`](/docs/providers/aws/r/elb.html#zone_id) for example.
    zone_id = ""

    # name - (Required) DNS domain name for a CloudFront distribution, S3 bucket, ELB, or another resource record set in this hosted zone.
    name = ""

    # type - (Required) The record type. Valid values are `A`, `AAAA`, `CAA`, `CNAME`, `MX`, `NAPTR`, `NS`, `PTR`, `SOA`, `SPF`, `SRV` and `TXT`.
    type = ""

    # name - (Required) The name of the record.
    name = ""

    # zone_id - (Required) The ID of the hosted zone to contain this record.
    zone_id = ""

    # ttl - (Optional) (Required for non-alias records) The TTL of the record.
    ttl = ""

    # records - (Optional) (Required for non-alias records) A string list of records.
    records = ""

    # set_identifier - (Optional) Unique identifier to differentiate records with routing policies from one another. Required if using `failover`, `geolocation`, `latency`, or `weighted` routing policies documented below.
    set_identifier = ""

    # health_check_id - (Optional) The health check the record should be associated with.
    health_check_id = ""

    # alias - (Optional) An alias block. Conflicts with `ttl` & `records`.
    alias = ""

    # failover_routing_policy - (Optional) A block indicating the routing behavior when associated health check fails. Conflicts with any other routing policy. Documented below.
    failover_routing_policy = ""

    # geolocation_routing_policy - (Optional) A block indicating a routing policy based on the geolocation of the requestor. Conflicts with any other routing policy. Documented below.
    geolocation_routing_policy = ""

    # latency_routing_policy - (Optional) A block indicating a routing policy based on the latency between the requestor and an AWS region. Conflicts with any other routing policy. Documented below.
    latency_routing_policy = ""

    # weighted_routing_policy - (Optional) A block indicating a weighted routing policy. Conflicts with any other routing policy. Documented below.
    weighted_routing_policy = ""

    # multivalue_answer_routing_policy - (Optional) A block indicating a multivalue answer routing policy. Conflicts with any other routing policy.
    multivalue_answer_routing_policy = ""

    # continent - (Optional) A two-letter continent code. See http://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/APIReference/API_GetGeoLocation.html for code details. Either `continent` or `country` must be specified.
    continent = ""

    # country - (Optional) A two-character country code or `*` to indicate a default resource record set.
    country = ""

    # subdivision - (Optional) A subdivision code for a country.
    subdivision = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "fqdn" - [FQDN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fully_qualified_domain_name) built using the zone domain and "name"
}

aws-resource-route53-zone.body:
resource "aws_route53_zone" "$1" {

aws-resource-security-group.description:
Provides a security group resource. ~> **NOTE on Security Groups and Security Group Rules:** Terraform currently
provides both a standalone [Security Group Rule resource](security_group_rule.html) (a single `ingress` or
`egress` rule), and a Security Group resource with `ingress` and `egress` rules
defined in-line. At this time you cannot use a Security Group with in-line rules
in conjunction with any Security Group Rule resources. Doing so will cause
a conflict of rule settings and will overwrite rules.

    from_port = ""

    # cidr_blocks - (Optional) List of CIDR blocks. Cannot be specified with `source_security_group_id`.

    # "id" - The ID of the security group rule
    # "type" - The type of rule, "ingress" or "egress"

aws-resource-security-group-rule.description:
Provides a security group rule resource. Represents a single `ingress` or
`egress` group rule, which can be added to external Security Groups. ~> **NOTE on Security Groups and Security Group Rules:** Terraform currently
provides both a standalone Security Group Rule resource (a single `ingress` or
`egress` rule), and a [Security Group resource](security_group.html) with `ingress` and `egress` rules
defined in-line. At this time you cannot use a Security Group with in-line rules
in conjunction with any Security Group Rule resources. Doing so will cause
a conflict of rule settings and will overwrite rules.

    # endpoint - (Required) The endpoint to send data to, the contents will vary with the protocol. (see below for more information)

    protocol = ""

    # topic_arn - (Required) The ARN of the SNS topic to subscribe to
    topic_arn = ""

    # endpoint_auto_confirms - (Optional) Boolean indicating whether the end point is capable of [auto confirming subscription](http://docs.aws.amazon.com/sns/latest/dg/SendMessageToHttp.html#SendMessageToHttp.prepare) e.g., PagerDuty (default is false)
    endpoint_auto_confirms = ""

    # confirmation_timeout_in_minutes - (Optional) Integer indicating number of minutes to wait in retying mode for fetching subscription arn before marking it as failure. Only applicable for http and https protocols (default is 1 minute).
    confirmation_timeout_in_minutes = ""

    # raw_message_delivery - (Optional) Boolean indicating whether or not to enable raw message delivery (the original message is directly passed, not wrapped in JSON with the original message in the message property) (default is false).
    raw_message_delivery = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ARN of the subscription
    # "topic_arn" - The ARN of the topic the subscription belongs to
    # "protocol" - The protocol being used
    # "endpoint" - The full endpoint to send data to (SQS ARN, HTTP(S) URL, Application ARN, SMS number, etc.)
    # "arn" - The ARN of the subscription stored as a more user-friendly property
}
aws-resource-sns-topic-subscription.description:
Provides a resource for subscribing to SNS topics. Requires that an SNS topic exist for the subscription to attach to.
This resource allows you to automatically place messages sent to SNS topics in SQS queues, send them as HTTP(S) POST requests
to a given endpoint, send SMS messages, or notify devices / applications. The most likely use case for Terraform users will
probably be SQS queues. ~> **NOTE:** If SNS topic and SQS queue are in different AWS regions it is important to place the "aws_sns_topic_subscription" into the terraform configuration of the region with the SQS queue. If "aws_sns_topic_subscription" is placed in the terraform configuration of the region with the SNS topic terraform will fail to create the subscription. ~> **NOTE:** Setup of cross-account subscriptions from SNS topics to SQS queues requires Terraform to have access to BOTH accounts. ~> **NOTE:** If SNS topic and SQS queue are in different AWS accounts but the same region it is important to place the "aws_sns_topic_subscription" into the terraform configuration of the account with the SQS queue. If "aws_sns_topic_subscription" is placed in the terraform configuration of the account with the SNS topic terraform creates the subscriptions but does not keep state and tries to re-create the subscription at every apply. ~> **NOTE:** If SNS topic and SQS queue are in different AWS accounts and different AWS regions it is important to recognize that the subscription needs to be initiated from the account with the SQS queue but in the region of the SNS topic.

    # launch_group - (Optional) A launch group is a group of spot instances that launch together and terminate together.
    launch_group = ""

    # block_duration_minutes - (Optional) The required duration for the Spot instances, in minutes. This value must be a multiple of 60 (60, 120, 180, 240, 300, or 360).
    block_duration_minutes = ""

    # instance_interruption_behavior - (Optional) Indicates whether a Spot instance stops or terminates when it is interrupted. Default is `terminate` as this is the current AWS behaviour.
    instance_interruption_behavior = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The Spot Instance Request ID.
    # "spot_bid_status" - The current [bid
    # "spot_request_state" The current [request
    # "spot_instance_id" - The Instance ID (if any) that is currently fulfilling
    # "public_dns" - The public DNS name assigned to the instance. For EC2-VPC, this
    # "public_ip" - The public IP address assigned to the instance, if applicable.
    # "private_dns" - The private DNS name assigned to the instance. Can only be
    # "private_ip" - The private IP address assigned to the instance
}
aws-resource-spot-instance-request.description:
Provides an EC2 Spot Instance Request resource. This allows instances to be
requested on the spot market. Terraform always creates Spot Instance Requests with a `persistent` type, which
means that for the duration of their lifetime, AWS will launch an instance
with the configured details if and when the spot market will accept the
requested price. On destruction, Terraform will make an attempt to terminate the associated Spot
Instance if there is one present. ~> **NOTE:** Because their behavior depends on the live status of the spot
market, Spot Instance Requests have a unique lifecycle that makes them behave
differently than other Terraform resources. Most importantly: there is __no
guarantee__ that a Spot Instance exists to fulfill the request at any given
point in time. See the [AWS Spot Instance
documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/using-spot-instances.html)
for more information.

aws-resource-sqs-queue.body:
resource "aws_sqs_queue" "$1" {
    # name - (Optional) This is the human-readable name of the queue. If omitted, Terraform will assign a random name.
    name = ""

    # name_prefix - (Optional) Creates a unique name beginning with the specified prefix. Conflicts with `name`.
    name_prefix = ""

    # visibility_timeout_seconds - (Optional) The visibility timeout for the queue. An integer from 0 to 43200 (12 hours). The default for this attribute is 30. For more information about visibility timeout, see [AWS docs](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/AboutVT.html).
    visibility_timeout_seconds = ""

    # message_retention_seconds - (Optional) The number of seconds Amazon SQS retains a message. Integer representing seconds, from 60 (1 minute) to 1209600 (14 days). The default for this attribute is 345600 (4 days).
    message_retention_seconds = ""

    # max_message_size - (Optional) The limit of how many bytes a message can contain before Amazon SQS rejects it. An integer from 1024 bytes (1 KiB) up to 262144 bytes (256 KiB). The default for this attribute is 262144 (256 KiB).
    max_message_size = ""

    # delay_seconds - (Optional) The time in seconds that the delivery of all messages in the queue will be delayed. An integer from 0 to 900 (15 minutes). The default for this attribute is 0 seconds.
    delay_seconds = ""

    # receive_wait_time_seconds - (Optional) The time for which a ReceiveMessage call will wait for a message to arrive (long polling) before returning. An integer from 0 to 20 (seconds). The default for this attribute is 0, meaning that the call will return immediately.
    receive_wait_time_seconds = ""

    # policy - (Optional) The JSON policy for the SQS queue
    policy = ""

    # redrive_policy - (Optional) The JSON policy to set up the Dead Letter Queue, see [AWS docs](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/SQSDeadLetterQueue.html). **Note:** when specifying `maxReceiveCount`, you must specify it as an integer (`5`), and not a string (`"5"`).
    redrive_policy = ""

    # fifo_queue - (Optional) Boolean designating a FIFO queue. If not set, it defaults to `false` making it standard.
    fifo_queue = ""

    # content_based_deduplication - (Optional) Enables content-based deduplication for FIFO queues. For more information, see the [related documentation](http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/FIFO-queues.html#FIFO-queues-exactly-once-processing)
    content_based_deduplication = ""

    # kms_master_key_id - (Optional) The ID of an AWS-managed customer master key (CMK) for Amazon SQS or a custom CMK. For more information, see [Key Terms](http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/sqs-server-side-encryption.html#sqs-sse-key-terms).
    kms_master_key_id = ""

    # kms_data_key_reuse_period_seconds - (Optional) The length of time, in seconds, for which Amazon SQS can reuse a data key to encrypt or decrypt messages before calling AWS KMS again. An integer representing seconds, between 60 seconds (1 minute) and 86,400 seconds (24 hours). The default is 300 (5 minutes).
    kms_data_key_reuse_period_seconds = ""

    # tags - (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the queue.
    tags = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The URL for the created Amazon SQS queue.
    # "arn" - The ARN of the SQS queue
}

aws-resource-sqs-queue-policy.body:
resource "aws_sqs_queue_policy" "$1" {
    # policy - (Required) The JSON policy for the SQS queue
    policy = ""

    # queue_url - (Required) The URL of the SQS Queue to which to attach the policy
    queue_url = ""

    # Exported Attributes
}
aws-resource-sqs-queue-policy.description:
Allows you to set a policy of an SQS Queue
while referencing ARN of the queue within the policy.

aws-resource-ssm-activation.body:
resource "aws_ssm_activation" "$1" {
    # iam_role - (Required) The IAM Role to attach to the managed instance.
    iam_role = ""

    # name - (Optional) The default name of the registerd managed instance.
    name = ""

    # description - (Optional) The description of the resource that you want to register.
    description = ""

    # expiration_date - (Optional) The date by which this activation request should expire. The default value is 24 hours.
    expiration_date = ""

    # registration_limit - (Optional) The maximum number of managed instances you want to register. The default value is 1 instance.
    registration_limit = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "activation_code" - The code the system generates when it processes the activation.
    # "name" - The default name of the registerd managed instance.
    # "description" - The description of the resource that was registered.
    # "expired" - If the current activation has expired.
    # "expiration_date" - The date by which this activation request should expire. The default value is 24 hours.
    # "iam_role" - The IAM Role attached to the managed instance.
    # "registration_limit" - The maximum number of managed instances you want to be registered. The default value is 1 instance.
    # "registration_count" - The number of managed instances that are currently registered using this activation.
}
aws-resource-ssm-activation.description: Registers an on-premises server or virtual machine with Amazon EC2 so that it can be managed using Run Command.

aws-resource-ssm-association.body:
resource "aws_ssm_association" "$1" {
    # name - (Required) The name of the SSM document to apply.
    name = ""

    # instance_id - (Optional) The instance id to apply an SSM document to.
    instance_id = ""

    # parameters - (Optional) Additional parameters to pass to the SSM document.
    parameters = ""

    # targets - (Optional) The targets (either instances or tags). Instances are specified using Key=instanceids,Values=instanceid1,instanceid2. Tags are specified using Key=tag name,Values=tag value. Only 1 target is currently supported by AWS.
    targets = ""

    # schedule_expression - (Optional) A cron expression when the association will be applied to the target(s).
    schedule_expression = ""

    # output_location - (Optional) An output location block. OutputLocation documented below.
    output_location = ""

    # document_version - (Optional) The document version you want to associate with the target(s). Can be a specific version or the default version.
    document_version = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "name" - The name of the SSM document to apply.
    # "instance_ids" - The instance id that the SSM document was applied to.
    # "parameters" - Additional parameters passed to the SSM document.
}
aws-resource-ssm-association.description: Associates an SSM Document to an instance.

aws-resource-ssm-document.body:
resource "aws_ssm_document" "$1" {
    # document_type - (Required) The type of the document. Valid document types include: `Command`, `Policy` and `Automation`
    document_type = ""

    # content - (Required) The json content of the document.
    content = ""

    # name - (Required) The name of the document.
    name = ""

    # permissions - (Optional) Additional Permissions to attach to the document. See [Permissions](#permissions) below for details.
    permissions = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "name" - The name of the document.
    # "content" -  The json content of the document.
    # "created_date" - The date the document was created.
    # "description" - The description of the document.
    # "schema_version" - The schema version of the document.
    # "document_type" - The type of document created.
    # "default_version" - The default version of the document.
    # "hash" - The sha1 or sha256 of the document content
    # "hash_type" - "Sha1" "Sha256". The hashing algorithm used when hashing the content.
    # "latest_version" - The latest version of the document.
    # "owner" - The AWS user account of the person who created the document.
    # "status" - "Creating", "Active" or "Deleting". The current status of the document.
    # "parameter" - The parameters that are available to this document.
    # "permissions" - The permissions of how this document should be shared.
    # "platform_types" - A list of OS platforms compatible with this SSM document, either "Windows" or "Linux".
}
aws-resource-ssm-document.description:
Provides an SSM Document resource ~> **NOTE on updating SSM documents:** Only documents with a schema version of 2.0
or greater can update their content once created, see [SSM Schema Features][1]. To update a document with an older
schema version you must recreate the resource.

aws-resource-ssm-maintenance-window.body:
resource "aws_ssm_maintenance_window" "$1" {
    # duration - (Required) The duration of the Maintenance Window in hours.
    duration = ""

    # cutoff - (Required) The number of hours before the end of the Maintenance Window that Systems Manager stops scheduling new tasks for execution.
    cutoff = ""

    # schedule - (Required) The schedule of the Maintenance Window in the form of a [cron](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/sysman-maintenance-cron.html) or rate expression.
    schedule = ""

    # name - (Required) The name of the maintenance window.
    name = ""

    # allow_unassociated_targets - (Optional) Whether targets must be registered with the Maintenance Window before tasks can be defined for those targets.
    allow_unassociated_targets = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the maintenance window.
}
aws-resource-ssm-maintenance-window.description: Provides an SSM Maintenance Window resource

aws-resource-ssm-maintenance-window-targ.body:
resource "aws_ssm_maintenance_window_target" "$1" {
    # targets - (Required) The targets (either instances or tags). Instances are specified using Key=instanceids,Values=instanceid1,instanceid2. Tags are specified using Key=tag name,Values=tag value.
    targets = ""

    # resource_type - (Required) The type of target being registered with the Maintenance Window. Possible values `INSTANCE`.
    resource_type = ""

    # window_id - (Required) The Id of the maintenance window to register the target with.
    window_id = ""

    # owner_information - (Optional) User-provided value that will be included in any CloudWatch events raised while running tasks for these targets in this Maintenance Window.
    owner_information = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the maintenance window target.
}
aws-resource-ssm-maintenance-window-targ.description: Provides an SSM Maintenance Window Target resource

aws-resource-ssm-maintenance-window-task.body:
resource "aws_ssm_maintenance_window_task" "$1" {
    # values - (Required) 
    values = ""

    # name - (Required) 
    name = ""

    # targets - (Required) The targets (either instances or window target ids). Instances are specified using Key=InstanceIds,Values=instanceid1,instanceid2. Window target ids are specified using Key=WindowTargetIds,Values=window target id1, window target id2.
    targets = ""

    # service_role_arn - (Required) The role that should be assumed when executing the task.
    service_role_arn = ""

    # task_arn - (Required) The ARN of the task to execute.
    task_arn = ""

    # task_type - (Required) The type of task being registered. The only allowed value is `RUN_COMMAND`.
    task_type = ""

    # max_errors - (Required) The maximum number of errors allowed before this task stops being scheduled.
    max_errors = ""

    # max_concurrency - (Required) The maximum number of targets this task can be run for in parallel.
    max_concurrency = ""

    # window_id - (Required) The Id of the maintenance window to register the task with.
    window_id = ""

    # priority - (Optional) The priority of the task in the Maintenance Window, the lower the number the higher the priority. Tasks in a Maintenance Window are scheduled in priority order with tasks that have the same priority scheduled in parallel.
    priority = ""

    # logging_info - (Optional) A structure containing information about an Amazon S3 bucket to write instance-level logs to. Documented below.
    logging_info = ""

    # task_parameters - (Optional) A structure containing information about parameters required by the particular `task_arn`. Documented below.
    task_parameters = ""

    # logging_info - (Optional) `logging_info` supports the following:
    logging_info = ""

    # task_parameters - (Optional) `task_parameters` supports the following:
    task_parameters = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the maintenance window task.
}
aws-resource-ssm-maintenance-window-task.description: Provides an SSM Maintenance Window Task resource

aws-resource-ssm-parameter.body:
resource "aws_ssm_parameter" "$1" {
    # value - (Required) The value of the parameter.
    value = ""

    # type - (Required) The type of the parameter. Valid types are `String`, `StringList` and `SecureString`.
    type = ""

    name = ""

    key_id = ""

    overwrite = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "name" - (Required) The name of the parameter.
    # "type" - (Required) The type of the parameter. Valid types are "String", "StringList" and "SecureString".
    # "value" - (Required) The value of the parameter.
}

aws-resource-ssm-patch-baseline.body:
resource "aws_ssm_patch_baseline" "$1" {
    # patch_filter - (Required) The patch filter group that defines the criteria for the rule. Up to 4 patch filters can be specified per approval rule using Key/Value pairs. Valid Keys are `PRODUCT | CLASSIFICATION | MSRC_SEVERITY | PATCH_ID`.
    patch_filter = ""

    # approve_after_days - (Required) The number of days after the release date of each patch matched by the rule the patch is marked as approved in the patch baseline. Valid Range: 0 to 100.
    approve_after_days = ""

    # name - (Required) The name of the patch baseline.
    name = ""

    # description - (Optional) The description of the patch baseline.
    description = ""

    # operating_system - (Optional) Defines the operating system the patch baseline applies to. Supported operating systems include `WINDOWS`, `AMAZON_LINUX`, `UBUNTU` and `REDHAT_ENTERPRISE_LINUX`. The Default value is `WINDOWS`.
    operating_system = ""

    # approved_patches_compliance_level - (Optional) Defines the compliance level for approved patches. This means that if an approved patch is reported as missing, this is the severity of the compliance violation. Valid compliance levels include the following: `CRITICAL`, `HIGH`, `MEDIUM`, `LOW`, `INFORMATIONAL`, `UNSPECIFIED`. The default value is `UNSPECIFIED`.
    approved_patches_compliance_level = ""

    # approved_patches - (Optional) A list of explicitly approved patches for the baseline.
    approved_patches = ""

    # rejected_patches - (Optional) A list of rejected patches.
    rejected_patches = ""

    # global_filter - (Optional) A set of global filters used to exclude patches from the baseline. Up to 4 global filters can be specified using Key/Value pairs. Valid Keys are `PRODUCT | CLASSIFICATION | MSRC_SEVERITY | PATCH_ID`.
    global_filter = ""

    # approval_rule - (Optional) A set of rules used to include patches in the baseline. up to 10 approval rules can be specified. Each approval_rule block requires the fields documented below.
    approval_rule = ""

    # compliance_level - (Optional) Defines the compliance level for patches approved by this rule. Valid compliance levels include the following: `CRITICAL`, `HIGH`, `MEDIUM`, `LOW`, `INFORMATIONAL`, `UNSPECIFIED`. The default value is `UNSPECIFIED`.
    compliance_level = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the patch baseline.
}
aws-resource-ssm-patch-baseline.description:
Provides an SSM Patch Baseline resource ~> **NOTE on Patch Baselines:** The `approved_patches` and `approval_rule` are 
both marked as optional fields, but the Patch Baseline requires that at least one
of them is specified.

aws-resource-ssm-patch-group.body:
resource "aws_ssm_patch_group" "$1" {
    # patch_group - (Required) The name of the patch group that should be registered with the patch baseline.
    patch_group = ""

    # baseline_id - (Required) The ID of the patch baseline to register the patch group with.
    baseline_id = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the patch baseline.
}
aws-resource-ssm-patch-group.description: Provides an SSM Patch Group resource

aws-resource-subnet.body:
resource "aws_subnet" "$1" {
    # vpc_id - (Required) The VPC ID.
    vpc_id = ""

    # cidr_block - (Required) The CIDR block for the subnet.
    cidr_block = ""

    # availability_zone - (Optional) The AZ for the subnet.
    availability_zone = ""

    # map_public_ip_on_launch - (Optional) Specify true to indicate
    map_public_ip_on_launch = ""

    # tags - (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
    tags = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the subnet
    # "availability_zone"- The AZ for the subnet.
    # "cidr_block" - The CIDR block for the subnet.
    # "vpc_id" - The VPC ID.
    # "ipv6_association_id" - The association ID for the IPv6 CIDR block.
    # "ipv6_cidr_block" - The IPv6 CIDR block.

aws-resource-volume-attachment.body:
resource "aws_volume_attachment" "$1" {
    # volume_id - (Required) ID of the Volume to be attached
    volume_id = ""

    # instance_id - (Required) ID of the Instance to attach to
    instance_id = ""

    # device_name - (Required) The device name to expose to the instance (for
    device_name = ""

    # force_detach - (Optional) (Optional, Boolean) Set to `true` if you want to force the
    force_detach = ""

    # skip_destroy - (Optional) (Optional, Boolean) Set this to true if you do not wish
    skip_destroy = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "device_name" - The device name exposed to the instance
    # "instance_id" - ID of the Instance
    # "volume_id" - ID of the Volume
}
aws-resource-volume-attachment.description:
Provides an AWS EBS Volume Attachment as a top level resource, to attach and
detach volumes from AWS Instances. ~> **NOTE on EBS block devices:** If you use `ebs_block_device` on an `aws_instance`, Terraform will assume management over the full set of non-root EBS block devices for the instance, and treats additional block devices as drift. For this reason, `ebs_block_device` cannot be mixed with external `aws_ebs_volume` + `aws_ebs_volume_attachment` resources for a given instance.

aws-resource-vpc.body:
resource "aws_vpc" "$1" {
    # cidr_block - (Required) The CIDR block for the VPC.
    cidr_block = ""

    # instance_tenancy - (Optional) A tenancy option for instances launched into the VPC
    instance_tenancy = ""

    # enable_dns_support - (Optional) A boolean flag to enable/disable DNS support in the VPC. Defaults true.
    enable_dns_support = ""

    # enable_dns_hostnames - (Optional) A boolean flag to enable/disable DNS hostnames in the VPC. Defaults false.
    enable_dns_hostnames = ""

    # enable_classiclink - (Optional) A boolean flag to enable/disable ClassicLink
    enable_classiclink = ""

    # enable_classiclink_dns_support - (Optional) A boolean flag to enable/disable ClassicLink DNS Support for the VPC.
    enable_classiclink_dns_support = ""

    # tags - (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
    tags = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the VPC
    # "cidr_block" - The CIDR block of the VPC
    # "instance_tenancy" - Tenancy of instances spin up within VPC.
    # "enable_dns_support" - Whether or not the VPC has DNS support
    # "enable_dns_hostnames" - Whether or not the VPC has DNS hostname support
    # "enable_classiclink" - Whether or not the VPC has Classiclink enabled
    # "main_route_table_id" - The ID of the main route table associated with
    # "default_network_acl_id" - The ID of the network ACL created by default on VPC creation
    # "default_security_group_id" - The ID of the security group created by default on VPC creation
    # "default_route_table_id" - The ID of the route table created by default on VPC creation
    # "ipv6_association_id" - The association ID for the IPv6 CIDR block.
    # "ipv6_cidr_block" - The IPv6 CIDR block.
}

aws-resource-vpc-dhcp-options.body:
resource "aws_vpc_dhcp_options" "$1" {
    # domain_name - (Optional) the suffix domain name to use by default when resolving non Fully Qualified Domain Names. In other words, this is what ends up being the `search` value in the `/etc/resolv.conf` file.
    domain_name = ""

    # domain_name_servers - (Optional) List of name servers to configure in `/etc/resolv.conf`. If you want to use the default AWS nameservers you should set this to `AmazonProvidedDNS`.
    domain_name_servers = ""

    # ntp_servers - (Optional) List of NTP servers to configure.
    ntp_servers = ""

    # netbios_name_servers - (Optional) List of NETBIOS name servers.
    netbios_name_servers = ""

    # netbios_node_type - (Optional) The NetBIOS node type (1, 2, 4, or 8). AWS recommends to specify 2 since broadcast and multicast are not supported in their network. For more information about these node types, see [RFC 2132](http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2132.txt).
    netbios_node_type = ""

    # tags - (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
    tags = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the DHCP Options Set.
}
aws-resource-vpc-dhcp-options.description: Provides a VPC DHCP Options resource.

aws-resource-vpc-dhcp-options-associatio.body:
resource "aws_vpc_dhcp_options_association" "$1" {
    # dhcp_options_id - (Required) The ID of the DHCP Options Set to associate to the VPC.
    dhcp_options_id = ""

    # vpc_id - (Required) The ID of the VPC to which we would like to associate a DHCP Options Set.
    vpc_id = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the DHCP Options Set Association.
}
aws-resource-vpc-dhcp-options-associatio.description: Provides a VPC DHCP Options Association resource.

aws-resource-vpc-endpoint.body:
resource "aws_vpc_endpoint" "$1" {
    # service_name - (Required) The AWS service name, in the form `com.amazonaws.region.service`.
    service_name = ""

    # vpc_id - (Required) The ID of the VPC in which the endpoint will be used.
    vpc_id = ""

    # policy - (Optional) A policy to attach to the endpoint that controls access to the service.
    policy = ""

    # route_table_ids - (Optional) One or more route table IDs.
    route_table_ids = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the VPC endpoint.
    # "prefix_list_id" - The prefix list ID of the exposed service.
    # "cidr_blocks" - The list of CIDR blocks for the exposed service.
}
aws-resource-vpc-endpoint.description:
Provides a VPC Endpoint resource. ~> **NOTE on VPC Endpoints and VPC Endpoint Route Table Associations:** Terraform provides
both a standalone [VPC Endpoint Route Table Association](vpc_endpoint_route_table_association.html)
(an association between a VPC endpoint and a single `route_table_id`) and a VPC Endpoint resource
with a `route_table_ids` attribute. Do not use the same route table ID in both a VPC Endpoint resource
and a VPC Endpoint Route Table Association resource. Doing so will cause a conflict of associations
and will overwrite the association.

aws-resource-vpc-endpoint-route-table-as.body:
resource "aws_vpc_endpoint_route_table_association" "$1" {
    # route_table_id - (Required) The ID of the routing table to be associated with the VPC endpoint.
    route_table_id = ""

    # vpc_endpoint_id - (Required) The ID of the VPC endpoint with which the routing table will be associated.
    vpc_endpoint_id = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the association.
}
aws-resource-vpc-endpoint-route-table-as.description:
Provides a resource to create an association between a VPC endpoint and routing table. ~> **NOTE on VPC Endpoints and VPC Endpoint Route Table Associations:** Terraform provides
both a standalone VPC Endpoint Route Table Association (an association between a VPC endpoint
and a single `route_table_id`) and a [VPC Endpoint](vpc_endpoint.html) resource with a `route_table_ids`
attribute. Do not use the same route table ID in both a VPC Endpoint resource and a VPC Endpoint Route
Table Association resource. Doing so will cause a conflict of associations and will overwrite the association.

aws-resource-vpc-peering.body:
resource "aws_vpc_peering_connection" "$1" {
    # vpc_id - (Required) The ID of the requester VPC.
    vpc_id = ""

    # peer_vpc_id - (Required) The ID of the VPC with which you are creating the VPC Peering Connection.
    peer_vpc_id = ""

    # peer_owner_id - (Optional) The AWS account ID of the owner of the peer VPC.
    peer_owner_id = ""

    # auto_accept - (Optional) Accept the peering (both VPCs need to be in the same AWS account).
    auto_accept = ""

    # accepter - (Optional) - An optional configuration block that allows for [VPC Peering Connection]
    accepter = ""

    # requester - (Optional) - A optional configuration block that allows for [VPC Peering Connection]
    requester = ""

    # tags - (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
    tags = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the VPC Peering Connection.
    # "accept_status" - The status of the VPC Peering Connection request.
}
aws-resource-vpc-peering.description:
Provides a resource to manage a VPC Peering Connection resource. -> **Note:** For cross-account (requester's AWS account differs from the accepter's AWS account) VPC Peering Connections
use the `aws_vpc_peering_connection` resource to manage the requester's side of the connection and
use the `aws_vpc_peering_connection_accepter` resource to manage the accepter's side of the connection.

aws-resource-vpc-peering-accepter.body:
resource "aws_vpc_peering_connection_accepter" "$1" {
    # vpc_peering_connection_id - (Required) The VPC Peering Connection ID to manage.
    vpc_peering_connection_id = ""

    # auto_accept - (Optional) Whether or not to accept the peering request. Defaults to `false`.
    auto_accept = ""

    # tags - (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
    tags = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the VPC Peering Connection.
    # "accept_status" - The status of the VPC Peering Connection request.
    # "vpc_id" - The ID of the accepter VPC.
    # "peer_vpc_id" - The ID of the requester VPC.
    # "peer_owner_id" - The AWS account ID of the owner of the requester VPC.
    # "accepter" - A configuration block that describes [VPC Peering Connection]
    # "requester" - A configuration block that describes [VPC Peering Connection]
}
aws-resource-vpc-peering-accepter.description:
Provides a resource to manage the accepter's side of a cross-account VPC Peering Connection. When a cross-account (requester's AWS account differs from the accepter's AWS account) VPC Peering Connection
is created, a VPC Peering Connection resource is automatically created in the accepter's account.
The requester can use the `aws_vpc_peering_connection` resource to manage its side of the connection
and the accepter can use the `aws_vpc_peering_connection_accepter` resource to "adopt" its side of the
connection into management.

aws-resource-vpn-connection.body:
resource "aws_vpn_connection" "$1" {
    # vpn_gateway_id - (Required) The ID of the virtual private gateway.
    vpn_gateway_id = ""

    # type - (Required) The type of VPN connection. The only type AWS supports at this time is "ipsec.1".
    type = ""

    # customer_gateway_id - (Required) The ID of the customer gateway.
    customer_gateway_id = ""

    # static_routes_only - (Optional) (Optional, Default `false`) Whether the VPN connection uses static routes exclusively. Static routes must be used for devices that don't support BGP.
    static_routes_only = ""

    # tags - (Optional) Tags to apply to the connection.
    tags = ""

    # Exported Attributes
}
aws-resource-vpn-connection.description:
Provides a VPN connection connected to a VPC. These objects can be connected to customer gateways, and allow you to establish tunnels between your network and the VPC. ~> **Note:** All arguments including `tunnel1_preshared_key` and `tunnel2_preshared_key` will be stored in the raw state as plain-text.
[Read more about sensitive data in state](/docs/state/sensitive-data.html).

aws-resource-vpn-connection-route.body:
resource "aws_vpn_connection_route" "$1" {
    # vpn_connection_id - (Required) The ID of the VPN connection.
    vpn_connection_id = ""

    # destination_cidr_block - (Required) The CIDR block associated with the local subnet of the customer network.
    destination_cidr_block = ""

    # Exported Attributes
}
aws-resource-vpn-connection-route.description: Provides a static route between a VPN connection and a customer gateway.

aws-resource-vpn-gateway-attachment.body:
resource "aws_vpn_gateway_attachment" "$1" {
    # vpn_gateway_id - (Required) The ID of the Virtual Private Gateway.
    vpn_gateway_id = ""

    # vpc_id - (Required) The ID of the VPC.
    vpc_id = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "vpc_id" - The ID of the VPC that Virtual Private Gateway is attached to.
    # "vpn_gateway_id" - The ID of the Virtual Private Gateway.
}
aws-resource-vpn-gateway-attachment.description:
Provides a Virtual Private Gateway attachment resource, allowing for an existing
hardware VPN gateway to be attached and/or detached from a VPC. -> **Note:** The [`aws_vpn_gateway`](vpn_gateway.html)
resource can also automatically attach the Virtual Private Gateway it creates
to an existing VPC by setting the [`vpc_id`](vpn_gateway.html#vpc_id) attribute accordingly.

aws-resource-vpn-gateway-route-propagati.body:
resource "aws_vpn_gateway_route_propagation" "$1" {
    # vpn_gateway_id - (Optional) The id of the `aws_vpn_gateway` to propagate routes from.
    vpn_gateway_id = ""

    # route_table_id - (Optional) The id of the `aws_route_table` to propagate routes into.
    route_table_id = ""

    # Exported Attributes
}
aws-resource-vpn-gateway-route-propagati.description:
Requests automatic route propagation between a VPN gateway and a route table. ~> **Note:** This resource should not be used with a route table that has
the `propagating_vgws` argument set. If that argument is set, any route
propagation not explicitly listed in its value will be removed.

aws-resource-vpn-gateway-x.body:
resource "aws_vpn_gateway" "$1" {
    # vpc_id - (Optional) The VPC ID to create in.
    vpc_id = ""

    # availability_zone - (Optional) The Availability Zone for the virtual private gateway.
    availability_zone = ""

    # tags - (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
    tags = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the VPN Gateway.
}
aws-resource-vpn-gateway-x.description: Provides a resource to create a VPC VPN Gateway.

aws-resource-wafregional-bytematchset.body:
resource "wafregional_byte_match_set" "$1" {
    # type - (Required) The part of the web request that you want AWS WAF to search for a specified string.
    type = ""

    # text_transformation - (Required) The formatting way for web request.
    text_transformation = ""

    # target_string - (Required) The value that you want AWS WAF to search for. The maximum length of the value is 50 bytes.
    target_string = ""

    # positional_constraint - (Required) Within the portion of a web request that you want to search.
    positional_constraint = ""

    # field_to_match - (Required) Settings for the ByteMatchTuple. FieldToMatch documented below.
    field_to_match = ""

    # name - (Required) The name or description of the ByteMatchSet.
    name = ""

    # byte_match_tuple - (Optional) 
    byte_match_tuple = ""

    # data - (Optional) When the value of Type is HEADER, enter the name of the header that you want AWS WAF to search, for example, User-Agent or Referer. If the value of Type is any other value, omit Data.
    data = ""

    # Exported Attributes
    # "id" - The ID of the WAF ByteMatchSet.
}
aws-resource-wafregional-bytematchset.description: Provides a WAF Regional Byte Match Set Resource for use with Application Load Balancer.
